  "response": "Let me clarify the differences between Visual Basic and Visual Studio, and provide information about languages supported by .NET Framework:\n\nVisual Basic (VB):\n- A programming language developed by Microsoft\n- Part of the .NET family of languages\n- Designed to be easy to learn and use\n- Provides a simple syntax for creating Windows applications\n- Available in two main versions:\n  1. Visual Basic .NET (VB.NET)\n  2. Visual Basic 6.0 (legacy version)\n\nVisual Studio:\n- An Integrated Development Environment (IDE)\n- Used for developing software applications\n- Supports multiple programming languages\n- Provides tools for coding, debugging, and deployment\n- Includes code editors, designers, and other development tools\n- Comes in different editions:\n  - Community\n  - Professional\n  - Enterprise\n\nLanguages Supported by .NET Framework:\n1. Primary .NET Languages:\n- C#\n- Visual Basic .NET (VB.NET)\n- F#\n\n2. Other Supported Languages:\n- C++/CLI\n- J# (deprecated)\n- Python (with specific .NET implementations)\n- JavaScript (with .NET frameworks)\n\n3. Additional Languages with .NET Support:\n- IronPython\n- IronRuby\n- Managed C++\n\nKey Points:\n- Visual Basic is a language\n- Visual Studio is an IDE that supports multiple languages\n- .NET Framework provides a common runtime environment for these languages",
